ford, Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England":"Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England"},"en":{"1418–1471":"1418–1471","1418–1479":"1418–1479","1452–1531":"1452–1531","1392–1420":"1392–1420","1410–1440":"1410–1440","1479":"1479","1455":"1455","1410":"1410","1531":"1531","1420":"1420","1452":"1452","1440":"1440","1471":"1471","after 1440":"after 1440","1392":"1392","1418":"1418","Worcester, Worcestershire, England":"Worcester, Worcestershire, England","The Lee, Buckinghamshire, England":"The Lee, Buckinghamshire, England","Stanford, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Stanford, Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England":"Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Corbet","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Corbett  .","History: Walter Corbet, a royal knight in 12th-century Scotland, was the first of that name in that kingdom. His 13th-century descendants were major landholders in the Borders, and in the 14th century they acquired lands in the North of Scotland."],"variants":[{"name":"Corbett","meanings":["English (West Midlands, of Norman origin): nickname from Old French <i>corbet</i> ‘raven’, probably denoting someone with dark hair or a dark complexion.","History: This is the name of a family descended from Hugh <i>Corbet</i>, a Norman baron who settled in Shropshire following the Norman Conquest. One of his descendants, Sir Richard Corbet, was granted land near Shrewsbury in 1223; since the 13th century, this place has been known as Moreton Corbet. The name was taken from Shropshire to Scotland in the 12th century and to northern Ireland in the 17th century, and thence to North America by at least one group of bearers of the name."]}]},{"name":"Catherine","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."],"variants":[{"name":"Catheryn","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Katherine","meanings":["Variant of   Katherine ."]},{"name":"Catharin","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathrine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathryn","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathrin","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Catharine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":37,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Catherine Corbet was born in 1418, in Shropshire, England, her father, Thomas Corbet, was 26 and her mother, Katherine Sole, was 8. She had at least 1 daughter with Sir John Blount. She died in 1471, in Cornwall, England, at the age of 53."},"et":{"1418–1471":"1418–1471","1418–1479":"1418–1479","1452–1531":"1452–1531","1392–1420":"1392–1420","1410–1440":"1410–1440","1479":"1479","1455":"1455","1410":"1410","1531":"1531","1420":"1420","1452":"1452","1440":"1440","1471":"1471","after 1440":"pärast 1440","1392":"1392","1418":"1418","Worcester, Worcestershire, England":"Worcester, Worcestershire, England","The Lee, Buckinghamshire, En